# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aaron-manby-ironmaster
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby was born at Albrighton, Shropshire on 15 November 1776 to Aaron Manby of Kingston, Jamaica and Jane Lane of Bentley.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] They had a son, Charles Manby, who became Secretary of the Institution of Civil Engineers.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1807 Manby married Sarah Ann Haskins, with whom he had one daughter, Sarah Maria (d.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The oldest three of them, John Richard (1813-1869), Joseph Lane (1814-1862), and Edward Oliver (1816-1864), also became civil engineers.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's working life was originally in banks on the Isle of Wight.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1812 Manby was managing partner of the Horseley Coal and Iron Co, Tipton, Staffordshire.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] It ran coal mines, blast furnaces to make iron, and assorted workshops.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby expanded the business into civil engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1813 Manby obtained patent No 3705 for a means of casting the slag from blast furnaces into blocks for building.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1815, the firm supplied a cast-iron swing bridge, possibly the first of Horseley's many iron bridges.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1821, diversifying into mechanical engineering, Manby obtained British Patent No 4558 for his "oscillating engine" designed for use in ships.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] That same year, Horseley Ironworks constructed the world's first seagoing iron steamboat, named the *Aaron Manby*, using his oscillating engine.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The boat was built at Tipton using temporary bolts, disassembled for transportation to London, and reassembled on the Thames in 1822, this time using permanent rivets.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Between 1819 and 1822, Manby started his engineering works at Charenton-le-Pont, near Paris, with the Scottish chemist Daniel Wilson as manager.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] This controversial move enabled France to stop buying engines made in England, which made Manby somewhat unpopular.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1822 Manby and Wilson's *Compagnie d'Éclairage par de Gaz Hydrogène* ('Hydrogen Gas Lighting Company') was granted the right to provide gas lighting for several streets in Paris.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] According to Michel Cotte, "The company Manby & Wilson is certainly the largest company of British origin which set up in France under the Restoration." Their *"Compagnie Anglaise"* ran until 1847, expanding to take in the Le Creusot ironworks.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's Horseley Ironworks profited from the growing canal trade, manufacturing canal bridges in the English Midlands including the Engine Arm Aqueduct (1825) and two roving bridges at Smethwick Junction (1828).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1845 Manby sold Horseley Ironworks to John Joseph Bramah (~1798 - 1846), nephew of the inventor and locksmith Joseph Bramah.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby-ironmaster] After returning from France in about 1840, he lived at Fulham, London, before retiring to the Isle of Wight where he died.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] Launched in 1821, *Aaron Manby* was the first steamship to be built of iron.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] She was the brainchild of the eccentric but far-seeing naval officer Captain (later Admiral) Charles Napier, who had conceived the idea of a fleet of steamships for service on the River Seine.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] The ship was named after the master of the Horseley Ironworks, Tipton, Staffordshire, where she was pre-fabricated to a design jointly formulated by Captain Napier, Aaron Manby and his son Charles.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] She was then shipped in pieces to Rotherhithe on the Thames and assembled there.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] Of 116 tons burthen, the ship was 120 feet (37 m) long.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] Her flat-bottomed hull was made of 1⁄4-inch-thick (6.4 mm) iron plate fastened to angle-iron ribs.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] There was one deck, of wood, and a bowsprit.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] The ship's distinctive profile boasted a single 47-foot-high (14 m) funnel.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] The engine was of the oscillating type, designed and patented (British Patent No 4558 of 1821) by Aaron Manby.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] The paddlewheels: were 12 feet (3.7 m) in diameter but only 2.5 feet (76 cm) wide, because the vessel's maximum beam was limited to 23 feet (7.0 m) for service on the Seine.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] Defying the prevailing wisdom of the day, the iron-hulled vessel not only floated but made 9 knots (10 mph; 17 km/h) and drew one foot (30 cm) less water than any other steamboat then operating.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] After trials in May 1822, *Aaron Manby* crossed the English Channel to Le Havre under Napier's command on 10 June, at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h), carrying passengers and freighted with a cargo of linseed and iron castings.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] The ship proceeded up the Seine to Paris, where she caused a great stir and where she was based for the next decade.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] This has been claimed (incorrectly) as the first passage from Britain to France by steam ship.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] There had been shorter crossings by wooden steamers, but Napier's was the first direct steam crossing from London to Paris and the first seagoing voyage by an iron ship anywhere.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] After some further channel voyages the ship was used for pleasure trips up and down the Seine.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] The use of iron plates for the hull, in place of wood, was widely copied in shipbuilding during the following decades.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/aaron-manby] Napier had conceived the ship as a first step towards an iron warship, and in this sense *Aaron Manby* could be considered a direct ancestor of the Royal Navy's first iron frigate, HMS *Warrior*, built the year of Napier's death.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The village has a railway station on the Shrewsbury to Wolverhampton Line, and is near to RAF Cosford and the M54 motorway.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] It is the most easterly settlement in Shropshire.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Immediately to the north is the hamlet and parish of Donington, which is separated from Albrighton by Humphreston Brook.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Mentioned in the Domesday Book of 1086 as *Albricston(e)* or the home/farm of Albric/Aethelbeorht, it received its charter granting Borough status in 1303, which was renewed in 1662 for rather unusual reasons.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The Borough status meant that there was a Justice of the Peace who could order the arrest of criminals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] After the charter's renewal in 1662 it seemed to lapse again by the 19th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] A Mace confirming its borough status was discovered for auction at Sotheby's and this was purchased for £359 in 1948.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The money was raised by local subscription under the guidance and perseverance of the Rev E E Wright.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] A small jail and stocks stood somewhere near to the Crown public house, whilst a room above it was used for various village meetings and transactions.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] A press article in 1884 discussing the history of the village's regular fairs stated that they were 'held on a wide open space called the Cross, where the cross roads are in the middle of the [village].
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The Market Hall stood in the midst of the space, with the lock-up under it, and the stocks and pinfold close by.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Rev Blakeway in his draft *History of Albrighton* (c.1810-1814) mentioned that the Market House 'stands in the middle of the [village] and has two arches'.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] It is not known when the Toll Shop/House and Market Hall/House were demolished.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The Rev Wright thought the buildings were more likely to be on the area of the village green but none of the early tithe maps show these buildings.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The parish church, dedicated to St Mary Magdalene was completed around 1181, and some rebuilding work was done in 1853.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] It is built of red sandstone in the Norman style.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The church contains an alabaster monument to Sir John Talbot (died 1555) and his wife Lady Frances Gifford, as well as the Albrighton Mace, which was donated to the village in 1663, by Lady Mary Talbot.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The east window of the church dates from the 14th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The church also contains the family tomb of the Talbot Family, including the final resting place of Charles Talbot, the only Duke of Shrewsbury, George Talbot, 9th Earl of Shrewsbury (a Catholic priest), and Francis Talbot, 11th Earl of Shrewsbury, among others.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The church is separated from the extremely close parish church of St Cuthbert (Donington) by Humphreston Brook.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The story is that two sisters disagreed about the nature of the architecture of the church, and so resolved to build their own churches right next to each other.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] St Cuthbert's Church is also very close to St Cuthbert's Well, a holy well and grade II listed building that is located within Donington and Albrighton Nature Reserve.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Humphreston Brook was dammed by a local miller in the 17th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] It now provides the boundary between the two parishes and feeds into Donington Pool, which is also part of the Donington and Albrighton Nature Reserve.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Blakeway's history refers to the pond as being called *Hall Pool,* as it was adjacent to Hall Orchard, which was a burial ground for Roman Catholics by the church of St Mary Magdalene.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] For most of the 14th century and into the 15th the manor of Albrighton, together with Ryton, was held by the Carles, Careles or Careless family.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The Carles were connected by marriage to the Lestranges (Lords Strange of Blackmere) and the Talbots.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Albrighton left the control of this family with the marriage of an heiress to a member of the Corbet family in the reign of Henry VI.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The Earl of Shrewsbury is the premier Earl of England and, until 1918, was the biggest land owner in Albrighton.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] They were originally the Talbot family (later Chetwynd-Talbot), many of whom are buried in Albrighton Church.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Early in the 17th century, Albrighton was noted for making buttons and then in the 18th century clock making flourished.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] By 1880 it was bricks, but by and large, agriculture was the main industry before the building of the railways.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The population of Albrighton in 1801 was 900.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The High Street has not been altered too much over the years.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The half timbered inns, Georgian facades and lime trees still make the street picturesque.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Some sources say the lime trees were planted in the 19th century by a Dr Orson Bidwell; others say a former Earl of Shrewsbury was responsible.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] In all probability, both of them planted trees and so may many other people if a tree was damaged or failed.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The diary of John Howell, tenant farmer of Beamish and House Farm, gives the year of planting as 1832.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Gas came to Albrighton in 1868 and the Gasometer was at the side of the railway goods yard.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The Cosford Waterworks were established in 1857 and water was first supplied to the village in 1895.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Electricity came in 1919 initially on overhead poles and later, during the 1950s, the cables were put underground.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] In 1967, the A41 road through the village was bypassed and it now curves around the northern part of the village.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The village green was much more important in the first half of 20th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] At the time of the First World War there were swings on it, political meetings were held there, an evangelist lady spent three days a year in a caravan giving out leaflets and talking to people, also a band gave concerts there.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Austin opened up the David Austin Plant Centre on the western edge of the village bordering the A464 road.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] David Austin Roses are renowned the world over for their roses and the site is open to the public providing a large tourist attraction in the village.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] In 1998, the village granted the Officers and Men of RAF Cosford the right to exercise through the village.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Traditionally, this is known as having the Freedom of a village, town or city, but because Albrighton is not a borough, true freedom status could not be granted.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] However, every two years, staff from RAF Cosford parade down the High Street.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] An electoral ward in the name of Albrighton exists.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] This ward includes the parish of Donington and at the 2011 census had a total population of 4,628.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] On 1 April 2025 the parish was abolished and merged with Boscobel and Donington to form "Albrighton and Donington".
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] In about 1840, while writing the book *The Old Curiosity Shop*, Charles Dickens wrote about Tong Church whilst staying at the Public House now known as The Harp.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] In July 1992 Anneka Rice and the *Challenge Anneka* series came to Albrighton and created a fishing pool for disabled people, known as the Albrighton Moat Project.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] She returned in July 2017 to celebrate 25 years of the project.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] In the summer of 2006, a storm broke out in Albrighton and parts of the village were flooded badly.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Albrighton has five educational establishments: Albrighton and Donington Nursery, St Mary's Church of England Primary School, Albrighton Primary School (formerly Albrighton Infant and Junior School), Birchfield School and St Mary's Nursery Group.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The Red House in Albrighton, run by a trust, has, of 2021, been a venue for community activities for over 50 years.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] It was awarded the Queen's Award for Voluntary Service for its volunteers' support of the community during the COVID pandemic, by converting the parish minibus into a mobile shop to provide food and other deliveries, and for 6 months had run a Community Support Group.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] The following people and military units have received the "Right of Approbation" of Albrighton.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] This is the Village Council's equivalent to the granting of the Freedom of the City.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/albrighton-east-shropshire] Villages in the United Kingdom are not legally allowed to award the "Freedom of the Village" according to the wording of the Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Act 2009.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In most cases, a canal has a series of dams and locks that create reservoirs of low speed current flow.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These reservoirs are referred to as *slack water levels*, often just called *levels*.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A canal can be called a **navigation canal** when it parallels a natural river and shares part of the latter's discharges and drainage basin, and leverages its resources by building dams and locks to increase and lengthen its stretches of slack water levels while staying in its valley.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A canal can cut across a drainage divide atop a ridge, generally requiring an external water source above the highest elevation.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The best-known example of such a canal is the Panama Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Many canals have been built at elevations, above valleys and other waterways.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canals with sources of water at a higher level can deliver water to a destination such as a city where water is needed.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Roman Empire's aqueducts were such water supply canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The term was once used to describe certain linear features on the surface of Mars, though modern imaging has shown this to be a misnomer.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A *navigation* is a series of channels that run roughly parallel to the valley and stream bed of an unimproved river.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A navigation always shares the drainage basin of the river.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A vessel uses the calm parts of the river itself as well as improvements, traversing the same changes in height.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A true *canal* is a channel that cuts across a drainage divide, making a navigable channel connecting two different drainage basins.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Since they cut across drainage divides, rather than following the natural water level, true canals are more difficult to construct and often need additional improvements, such as viaducts and aqueducts.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Historically, canals were of immense importance to the commerce, development, growth and vitality of a civilization.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The movement of bulk raw materials such as coal and ores—practically a prerequisite for further urbanization and industrialization — were difficult and only marginally affordable to move without water transport.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The movement of bulk raw materials, facilitated by canals, fueled the Industrial Revolution, leading to new research disciplines, new industries and economies of scale, raising the standard of living for industrialized societies.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The few canals still in operation in the 21st century are a fraction of the number that were once maintained during the earlier part of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Their replacement was gradual, beginning first in the United Kingdom in the 1840s, where canal shipping was first augmented and later superseded by the much faster, less geographically constrained, and generally cheaper to maintain railway system.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] By the early 1880s, many canals could not compete with rail transport and were abandoned.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In the 20th century, oil was increasingly the heating fuel of choice, and the volume of coal shipments began to decrease.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] After the First World War, technological advances in motor trucks as well as expanding road networks saw increasing amounts of freight being transported by road, and the last small US barge canals saw a steady decline in cargo ton-miles.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Today, most ship canals (intended for larger, oceangoing vessels) primarily service bulk cargo and large ship transportation industries.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The longest extant canal today, the Grand Canal in northern China, still remains in heavy use, especially the portion south of the Yellow River.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It stretches from Beijing to Hangzhou at 1,794 kilometres (1,115 miles).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Smaller transportation canals can carry barges or narrowboats, while ship canals allow seagoing ships to travel to an inland port (e.g., Manchester Ship Canal), or from one sea or ocean to another (e.g., Caledonian Canal, Panama Canal).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] At their simplest, canals consist of a trench filled with water.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Depending on the stratum the canal passes through, it may be necessary to line the cut with some form of watertight material such as clay or concrete.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] When this is done with clay, it is known as puddling.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canals need to be level, and while small irregularities in the lie of the land can be dealt with through cuttings and embankments, for larger deviations other approaches have been adopted.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The most common is the pound lock, which consists of a chamber within which the water level can be raised or lowered connecting either two pieces of canal at a different level or the canal with a river or the sea.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] When there is a hill to be climbed, flights of many locks in short succession may be used.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Prior to the development of the (double-gated) pound lock in 10th-century China and 15th-century Europe, vessels had to ascend and descend either with flash locks, consisting of a single gate, or with ramps, sometimes equipped with rollers.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Flash locks were cumbersome and only usable where there was plenty of water available.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Cycling a lock uses a large amount of water, so builders have adopted other approaches for situations where little water is available.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These include boat lifts, such as the Falkirk Wheel, which use a caisson of water in which boats float while being moved between two levels; and inclined planes where a caisson is hauled up a steep railway.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The crossing of a stream, road or valley, where the delay caused by a flight of locks at either side would be unacceptable, may be achieved by the construction of a navigable aqueduct, such as the Pontcysyllte Aqueduct (now a UNESCO World Heritage Site) across the valley of the River Dee in Wales.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Another option for dealing with hills is to tunnel through them.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] An example of this approach is the Harecastle Tunnel on the Trent and Mersey Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Tunnels are only practical for smaller canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Some canals attempted to keep changes in level down to a minimum.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These canals known as contour canals would take longer, winding routes, along which the land was a uniform altitude.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Other, generally later, canals took more direct routes requiring the use of various methods to deal with the change in level.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canals have various features to tackle the problem of water supply.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In cases, like the Suez Canal, the canal is open to the sea.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Where the canal is not at sea level, a number of approaches have been adopted.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Taking water from existing rivers or springs was an option in some cases, sometimes supplemented by other methods to deal with seasonal variations in flow.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Where such sources were unavailable, reservoirs – either separate from the canal or built into its course – and back pumping were used to provide the required water.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In other cases, water pumped from mines was used to feed the canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In certain cases, extensive "feeder canals" were built to bring water from sources located far from the canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Where large amounts of goods are loaded or unloaded such as at the end of a canal, a canal basin may be built.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This would normally be a section of water wider than the general canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In some cases, the canal basins contain wharfs and cranes to assist with movement of goods.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] When a section of the canal needs to be sealed off so it can be drained for maintenance stop planks are frequently used.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These consist of planks of wood placed across the canal to form a dam.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] They are generally placed in pre-existing grooves in the canal bank.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] On more modern canals, "guard locks" or gates were sometimes placed to allow a section of the canal to be quickly closed off, either for maintenance, or to prevent a major loss of water due to a canal breach.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A *canal fall*, or canal drop, is a vertical drop in the canal bed.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These are built when the natural ground slope is steeper than the desired canal gradient.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] They are constructed so the falling water's kinetic energy is dissipated in order to prevent it from scouring the bed and sides of the canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A canal fall is constructed by cut and fill.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It may be combined with a regulator, bridge, or other structure to save costs.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] There are various types of canal falls, based on their shape.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] One type is the ogee fall, where the drop follows an s-shaped curve to create a smooth transition and reduce turbulence.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] However, this smooth transition does not dissipate the water's kinetic energy, which leads to heavy scouring.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] As a result, the canal needs to be reinforced with concrete or masonry to protect it from eroding.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Another type of canal fall is the vertical fall, which is "simple and economical".
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These feature a "cistern", or depressed area just downstream from the fall, to "cushion" the water by providing a deep pool for its kinetic energy to be diffused in.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Vertical falls work for drops of up to 1.5 m (5 ft) in height, and for discharge of up to 15 cubic metres per second (530 cu ft/s).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The transport capacity of pack animals and carts is limited.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A mule can carry a 100-kilogram (250 lb) maximum load over a journey of several days or weeks, though much more for shorter distances and periods with appropriate rest.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Transport over water is much more efficient and cost-effective for large cargoes.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The oldest known canals were irrigation canals, built in Mesopotamia c.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Indus Valley civilization in what is now Pakistan and Northwestern India (c.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] 3000 BC) had sophisticated irrigation and storage systems developed, including the reservoirs built at Girnar in 3000 BC.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This is the first time that such planned civil project had taken place in the ancient world.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In Egypt, canals date back at least to the time of Pepi I Meryre (reigned 2332–2283 BC), who ordered a canal built to bypass the cataract on the Nile near Aswan.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Caoyun System of canals was essential for imperial taxation, which was largely assessed in kind and involved enormous shipments of rice and other grains.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] By far the longest canal was the Grand Canal of China, still the longest canal in the world today and the oldest extant one.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It is 1,794 kilometres (1,115 mi) long and was built to carry the Emperor Yang Guang between Zhuodu (Beijing) and Yuhang (Hangzhou).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The project began in 605 and was completed in 609, although much of the work combined older canals, the oldest section of the canal existing since at least 486 BC.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Even in its narrowest urban sections it is rarely less than 30 metres (98 ft) wide.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In the 5th century BC, Achaemenid king Xerxes I of Persia ordered the construction of the Xerxes Canal through the base of Mount Athos peninsula, Chalkidiki, northern Greece.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It was constructed as part of his preparations for the Second Persian invasion of Greece, a part of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It is one of the few monuments left by the Persian Empire in Europe.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Greek engineers were also among the first to use canal locks, by which they regulated the water flow in the Ancient Suez Canal as early as the 3rd century BC.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Hohokam was a society in the North American Southwest in what is now part of Arizona, United States, and Sonora, Mexico.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Their irrigation systems supported the largest population in the Southwest by 1300 AD.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Archaeologists working at a major archaeological dig in the 1990s in the Tucson Basin, along the Santa Cruz River, identified a culture and people that may have been the ancestors of the Hohokam.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This prehistoric group occupied southern Arizona as early as 2000 BC, and in the Early Agricultural period grew corn, lived year-round in sedentary villages, and developed sophisticated irrigation canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The large-scale Hohokam irrigation network in the Phoenix metropolitan area was the most complex in ancient North America.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A portion of the ancient canals has been renovated for the Salt River Project and now helps to supply the city's water.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Sinhalese constructed the 87 km (54 mi) Yodha Ela in 459 AD as a part of their extensive irrigation network which functioned in a way of a moving reservoir due to its single banking aspect to manage the canal pressure with the influx of water.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It was also designed as an elongated reservoir passing through traps creating 66 mini catchments as it flows from Kala Wewa to Thissa Wawa.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The canal was not designed for the quick conveying of water from Kala Wewa to Thissa Wawa but to create a mass of water between the two reservoirs, which would in turn provide for agriculture and the use of humans and animals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] They also achieved a rather low gradient for its time.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The canal is still in use after renovation.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In the Middle Ages, water transport was several times cheaper and faster than transport overland.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This was because long-haul roads were unpaved, more often than not too narrow for carts, much less wagons, and in poor condition, wending their way through forests, marshy or muddy quagmires as often as unimproved but dry footing.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In that era, as today, greater cargoes, especially bulk goods and raw materials, could be transported by ship far more economically than by land; in the pre-railroad days of the industrial revolution, water transport was the gold standard of fast transportation.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The first artificial canal in Western Europe was the Fossa Carolina built at the end of the 8th century under personal supervision of Charlemagne.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In Britain, the Glastonbury Canal is believed to be the first post-Roman canal and was built in the middle of the 10th century to link the River Brue at Northover with Glastonbury Abbey, a distance of about 1.75 kilometres (1,900 yd).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Its initial purpose is believed to be the transport of building stone for the abbey, but later it was used for delivering produce, including grain, wine and fish, from the abbey's outlying properties.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It remained in use until at least the 14th century, but possibly as late as the mid-16th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] More lasting and of more economic impact were canals like the Naviglio Grande built between 1127 and 1257 to connect Milan with the river Ticino.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Naviglio Grande is the most important of the lombard "navigli" and the oldest functioning canal in Europe.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Later, canals were built in the Netherlands and Flanders to drain the polders and assist transportation of goods and people.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canal building was revived in this age because of commercial expansion from the 12th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] River navigations were improved progressively by the use of single, or flash locks.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Taking boats through these used large amounts of water leading to conflicts with watermill owners and to correct this, the pound or chamber lock first appeared, in the 10th century in China and in Europe in 1373 in Vreeswijk, Netherlands.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Another important development was the mitre gate, which was, it is presumed, introduced in Italy by Bertola da Novate in the 16th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This allowed wider gates and also removed the height restriction of guillotine locks.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] To break out of the limitations caused by river valleys, the first summit level canals were developed with the Grand Canal of China in 581–617 AD whilst in Europe the first, also using single locks, was the Stecknitz Canal in Germany in 1398.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In the Songhai Empire of West Africa, several canals were constructed under Sunni Ali and Askia Muhammad I between Kabara and Timbuktu in the 15th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These were used primarily for irrigation and transport.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Sunni Ali also attempted to construct a canal from the Niger River to Walata to facilitate conquest of the city but his progress was halted when he went to war with the Mossi Kingdoms.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Around 1500–1800 the first summit level canal to use pound locks in Europe was the Briare Canal connecting the Loire and Seine (1642), followed by the more ambitious Canal du Midi (1683) connecting the Atlantic to the Mediterranean.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This included a staircase of 8 locks at Béziers, a 157-metre (515 ft) tunnel, and three major aqueducts.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canal building progressed steadily in Germany in the 17th and 18th centuries with three great rivers, the Elbe, Oder and Weser being linked by canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In post-Roman Britain, the first early modern period canal built appears to have been the Exeter Canal, which was surveyed in 1563, and open in 1566.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It was constructed in 1639 to provide water power for mills.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In Russia, the Volga–Baltic Waterway, a nationwide canal system connecting the Baltic Sea and Caspian Sea via the Neva and Volga rivers, was opened in 1718.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The modern canal system was mainly a product of the 18th century and early 19th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It came into being because the Industrial Revolution (which began in Britain during the mid-18th century) demanded an economic and reliable way to transport goods and commodities in large quantities.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] By the early 18th century, river navigations such as the Aire and Calder Navigation were becoming quite sophisticated, with pound locks and longer and longer "cuts" (some with intermediate locks) to avoid circuitous or difficult stretches of river.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Eventually, the experience of building long multi-level cuts with their own locks gave rise to the idea of building a "pure" canal, a waterway designed on the basis of where goods needed to go, not where a river happened to be.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The claim for the first pure canal in Great Britain is debated between "Sankey" and "Bridgewater" supporters.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The first true canal in what is now the United Kingdom was the Newry Canal in Northern Ireland constructed by Thomas Steers in 1741.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] However, "Bridgewater" supporters point out that the last quarter-mile of the navigation is indeed a canalized stretch of the Brook, and that it was the Bridgewater Canal (less obviously associated with an existing river) that captured the popular imagination and inspired further canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In the mid-eighteenth century the 3rd Duke of Bridgewater, who owned a number of coal mines in northern England, wanted a reliable way to transport his coal to the rapidly industrializing city of Manchester.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] He commissioned the engineer James Brindley to build a canal for that purpose.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Brindley's design included an aqueduct carrying the canal over the River Irwell.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This was an engineering wonder which immediately attracted tourists.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The construction of this canal was funded entirely by the Duke and was called the Bridgewater Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It opened in 1761 and was the first major British canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The new canals proved highly successful.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The boats on the canal were horse-drawn with a towpath alongside the canal for the horse to walk along.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This horse-drawn system proved to be highly economical and became standard across the British canal network.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Commercial horse-drawn canal boats could be seen on the UK's canals until as late as the 1950s, although by then diesel-powered boats, often towing a second unpowered boat, had become standard.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The canal boats could carry thirty tons at a time with only one horse pulling – more than ten times the amount of cargo per horse that was possible with a cart.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Because of this huge increase in supply, the Bridgewater canal reduced the price of coal in Manchester by nearly two-thirds within just a year of its opening.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Bridgewater was also a huge financial success, with it earning what had been spent on its construction within just a few years.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This success proved the viability of canal transport, and soon industrialists in many other parts of the country wanted canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] After the Bridgewater canal, early canals were built by groups of private individuals with an interest in improving communications.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In Staffordshire the famous potter Josiah Wedgwood saw an opportunity to bring bulky cargoes of clay to his factory doors and to transport his fragile finished goods to market in Manchester, Birmingham or further away, by water, minimizing breakages.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Within just a few years of the Bridgewater's opening, an embryonic national canal network came into being, with the construction of canals such as the Oxford Canal and the Trent and Mersey Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The new canal system was both cause and effect of the rapid industrialization of The Midlands and the north.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The period between the 1770s and the 1830s is often referred to as the "Golden Age" of British canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In a further development, there was often out-and-out speculation, where people would try to buy shares in a newly floated company to sell them on for an immediate profit, regardless of whether the canal was ever profitable, or even built.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] During this period of "canal mania", huge sums were invested in canal building, and although many schemes came to nothing, the canal system rapidly expanded to nearly 6,400 kilometres (4,000 mi) in length.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Many rival canal companies were formed and competition was rampant.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Perhaps the best example was Worcester Bar in Birmingham, a point where the Worcester and Birmingham Canal and the Birmingham Canal Navigations Main Line were only seven feet apart.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] For many years, a dispute about tolls meant that goods travelling through Birmingham had to be portaged from boats in one canal to boats in the other.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canal companies were initially chartered by individual states in the United States.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These early canals were constructed, owned, and operated by private joint-stock companies.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Four were completed when the War of 1812 broke out; these were the South Hadley Canal (opened 1795) in Massachusetts, Santee Canal (opened 1800) in South Carolina, the Middlesex Canal (opened 1802) also in Massachusetts, and the Dismal Swamp Canal (opened 1805) in Virginia.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Erie Canal (opened 1825) was chartered and owned by the state of New York and financed by bonds bought by private investors.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Erie canal runs about 584 kilometres (363 mi) from Albany, New York, on the Hudson River to Buffalo, New York, at Lake Erie.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Hudson River connects Albany to the Atlantic port of New York City and the Erie Canal completed a navigable water route from the Atlantic Ocean to the Great Lakes.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The canal contains 36 locks and encompasses a total elevation differential of around 172 m (565 ft).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Erie Canal with its easy connections to most of the US mid-west and New York City soon quickly paid back all its invested capital (US$7 million) and started turning a profit.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] By cutting transportation costs in half or more it became a large profit center for Albany and New York City as it allowed the cheap transportation of many of the agricultural products grown in the mid west of the United States to the rest of the world.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] From New York City these agricultural products could easily be shipped to other US states or overseas.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Assured of a market for their farm products the settlement of the US mid-west was greatly accelerated by the Erie Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The profits generated by the Erie Canal project started a canal building boom in the United States that lasted until about 1850 when railroads started becoming seriously competitive in price and convenience.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Blackstone Canal (finished in 1828) in Massachusetts and Rhode Island fulfilled a similar role in the early industrial revolution between 1828 and 1848.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Blackstone Valley was a major contributor of the American Industrial Revolution where Samuel Slater built his first textile mill.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A **power canal** refers to a canal used for hydraulic power generation, rather than for transport.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Nowadays power canals are built almost exclusively as parts of hydroelectric power stations.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Parts of the United States, particularly in the Northeast, had enough fast-flowing rivers that water power was the primary means of powering factories (usually textile mills) until after the American Civil War.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] For example, Lowell, Massachusetts, considered to be "The Cradle of the American Industrial Revolution," has 10 kilometres (6 mi) of canals, built from around 1790 to 1850, that provided water power and a means of transportation for the city.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The output of the system is estimated at 7,500 kilowatts (10,000 hp).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Other cities with extensive power canal systems include Lawrence, Massachusetts, Holyoke, Massachusetts, Manchester, New Hampshire, and Augusta, Georgia.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The most notable power canal was built in 1862 for the Niagara Falls Hydraulic Power and Manufacturing Company.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Competition, from railways from the 1830s and roads in the 20th century, made the smaller canals obsolete for most commercial transport, and many of the British canals fell into decay.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Only the Manchester Ship Canal and the Aire and Calder Canal bucked this trend.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Yet in other countries canals grew in size as construction techniques improved.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] During the 19th century in the US, the length of canals grew from 160 kilometres (100 mi) to over 6,400 kilometres (4,000 mi), with a complex network making the Great Lakes navigable, in conjunction with Canada, although some canals were later drained and used as railroad rights-of-way.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In the United States, navigable canals reached into isolated areas and brought them in touch with the world beyond.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] By 1825 the Erie Canal, 584 kilometres (363 mi) long with 36 locks, opened up a connection from the populated Northeast to the Great Lakes.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Settlers flooded into regions serviced by such canals, since access to markets was available.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Erie Canal (as well as other canals) was instrumental in lowering the differences in commodity prices between these various markets across America.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The canals caused price convergence between different regions because of their reduction in transportation costs, which allowed Americans to ship and buy goods from farther distances much cheaper.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Ohio built many miles of canal, Indiana had working canals for a few decades, and the Illinois and Michigan Canal connected the Great Lakes to the Mississippi River system until replaced by a channelized river waterway.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Three major canals with very different purposes were built in what is now Canada.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The first Welland Canal, which opened in 1829 between Lake Ontario and Lake Erie, bypassing Niagara Falls and the Lachine Canal (1825), which allowed ships to skirt the nearly impassable rapids on the St.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Lawrence River at Montreal, were built for commerce.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Rideau Canal, completed in 1832, connects Ottawa on the Ottawa River to Kingston, Ontario on Lake Ontario.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Rideau Canal was built as a result of the War of 1812 to provide military transportation between the British colonies of Upper Canada and Lower Canada as an alternative to part of the St.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Lawrence River, which was susceptible to blockade by the United States.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In France, a steady linking of all the river systems – Rhine, Rhône, Saône and Seine – and the North Sea was boosted in 1879 by the establishment of the Freycinet gauge, which specified the minimum size of locks.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canal traffic doubled in the first decades of the 20th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Many notable sea canals were completed in this period, starting with the Suez Canal (1869) – which carries tonnage many times that of most other canals – and the Kiel Canal (1897), though the Panama Canal was not opened until 1914.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In the 19th century, a number of canals were built in Japan including the Biwako canal and the Tone canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] These canals were partially built with the help of engineers from the Netherlands and other countries.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A major question was how to connect the Atlantic and the Pacific with a canal through narrow Central America.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] (The Panama Railroad opened in 1855.) The original proposal was for a sea-level canal through what is today Nicaragua, taking advantage of the relatively large Lake Nicaragua.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This canal has never been built in part because of political instability, which scared off potential investors.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] It remains an active project (the geography has not changed), and in the 2010s Chinese involvement was developing.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The second choice for a Central American canal was a Panama Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The De Lesseps company, which ran the Suez Canal, first attempted to build a Panama Canal in the 1880s.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The difficulty of the terrain and weather (rain) encountered caused the company to go bankrupt.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] High worker mortality from disease also discouraged further investment in the project.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] DeLesseps' abandoned excavating equipment sits, isolated decaying machines, today tourist attractions.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Twenty years later, an expansionist United States, that just acquired colonies after defeating Spain in the 1898 Spanish–American War, and whose Navy became more important, decided to reactivate the project.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The United States and Colombia did not reach agreement on the terms of a canal treaty (see Hay–Herrán Treaty).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Panama, which did not have (and still does not have) a land connection with the rest of Colombia, was already thinking of independence.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In 1903 the United States, with support from Panamanians who expected the canal to provide substantial wages, revenues, and markets for local goods and services, took Panama province away from Colombia, and set up a puppet republic (Panama).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Its currency, the Balboa – a name that suggests the country began as a way to get from one hemisphere to the other – was a replica of the US dollar.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The US dollar was and remains legal tender (used as currency).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A US military zone, the Canal Zone, 16 kilometres (10 mi) wide, with US military stationed there (bases, 2 TV stations, channels 8 and 10, Pxs, a US-style high school), split Panama in half.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Canal – a major engineering project – was built.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The US did not feel that conditions were stable enough to withdraw until 1979.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The withdrawal from Panama contributed to President Jimmy Carter's defeat in 1980.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Large-scale ship canals such as the Panama Canal and Suez Canal continue to operate for cargo transportation, as do European barge canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Due to globalization, they are becoming increasingly important, resulting in expansion projects such as the Panama Canal expansion project.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The expanded canal began commercial operation on 26 June 2016.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The new set of locks allow transit of larger, Post-Panamax and New Panamax ships.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The narrow early industrial canals, however, have ceased to carry significant amounts of trade and many have been abandoned to navigation, but may still be used as a system for transportation of untreated water.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In some cases railways have been built along the canal route, an example being the Croydon Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] A movement that began in Britain and France to use the early industrial canals for pleasure boats, such as hotel barges, has spurred rehabilitation of stretches of historic canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In some cases, abandoned canals such as the Kennet and Avon Canal have been restored and are now used by pleasure boaters.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In Britain, canalside housing has also proven popular in recent years.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The Seine–Nord Europe Canal is being developed into a major transportation waterway, linking France with Belgium, Germany, and the Netherlands.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canals have found another use in the 21st century, as easements for the installation of fibre optic telecommunications network cabling, avoiding having them buried in roadways while facilitating access and reducing the hazard of being damaged from digging equipment.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canals are still used to provide water for agriculture.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] An extensive canal system exists within the Imperial Valley in the Southern California desert to provide irrigation to agriculture within the area.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canals are so deeply identified with Venice that many canal cities have been nicknamed *"the Venice of…"*.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The city is built on marshy islands, with wooden piles supporting the buildings, so that the land is man-made rather than the waterways.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] The islands have a long history of settlement; by the 12th century, Venice was a powerful city state.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Amsterdam was built in a similar way, with buildings on wooden piles.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Many Amsterdam canals were built as part of fortifications.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] They became *grachten* when the city was enlarged and houses were built alongside the water.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Its nickname as the "Venice of the North" is shared with Hamburg of Germany, St.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Petersburg of Russia and Bruges of Belgium.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Suzhou was dubbed the "Venice of the East" by Marco Polo during his travels there in the 13th century, with its modern canalside Pingjiang Road and Shantang Street becoming major tourist attractions.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Other nearby cities including Nanjing, Shanghai, Wuxi, Jiaxing, Huzhou, Nantong, Taizhou, Yangzhou, and Changzhou are located along the lower mouth of the Yangtze River and Lake Tai, yet another source of small rivers and creeks, which have been canalized and developed for centuries.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Liverpool Maritime Mercantile City was a UNESCO World Heritage Site near the centre of Liverpool, England, where a system of intertwining waterways and docks is now being developed for mainly residential and leisure use.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Canal estates (sometimes known as bayous in the United States) are a form of subdivision popular in cities like Miami, Texas City, Texas and the Gold Coast, Queensland; the Gold Coast has over 890 km (550 mi) of residential canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Wetlands are difficult areas upon which to build housing estates, so dredging part of the wetland down to a navigable channel provides fill to build up another part of the wetland above the flood level for houses.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Land is built up in a finger pattern that provides a suburban street layout of waterfront housing blocks.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Inland canals have often had boats specifically built for them.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] An example of this is the British narrowboat, which is up to 22 metres (72 ft) long and 2.1 metres (7 ft) wide and was primarily built for British Midland canals.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] In this case the limiting factor was the size of the locks.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] This is also the limiting factor on the Panama canal where Panamax ships were limited to a length of 289.56 m (950 ft) and a beam of 32.31 m (106 ft) until 26 June 2016 when the opening of larger locks allowed for the passage of larger New Panamax ships.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] For the lockless Suez Canal the limiting factor for Suezmax ships is generally draft, which is limited to 16 m (52.5 ft).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] At the other end of the scale, tub-boat canals such as the Bude Canal were limited to boats of under 10 tons for much of their length due to the capacity of their inclined planes or boat lifts.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/canal] Most canals have a limit on height imposed either by bridges or by tunnels.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] The Charenton psychiatric hospital is located in the neighbouring commune of Charenton-Saint-Maurice, which changed its name in 1842 to Saint-Maurice.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] A Bronze Age hoard of weapons was found in the river Seine at Charenton in the late 19th century.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] Comprising swords, axes, spearheads and other miscellaneous objects, it is now in the British Museum in London.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] Charenton was always a point of importance for the defence of the capital, and was frequently the scene of bloody conflicts.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] The Fort de Charenton, located in neighbouring Maisons-Alfort but intended to defend Charenton, is one of the older forts of the Paris defence.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] The Hôtel de Ville was built as a private residence in 1612.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] In the 16th and 17th centuries, Charenton was the scene of the ecclesiastical councils of the Protestant party, which had its principal church in the town.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] In the now-named commune of Saint-Maurice, adjoining Charenton to the east, is the Hospice de Charenton, a psychiatric hospital, the foundation of which dates from 1641.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] Until the time of the Revolution it was used as a general hospital, and even as a prison, but from 1802 onwards it was specially appropriated to the treatment of mental illness.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] On 1 January 1860, the City of Paris was enlarged by annexing neighbouring communes.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] On that occasion, half of the commune of Bercy was annexed to the city of the Paris, and the remaining half was annexed to Charenton-le-Pont.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] In 1929, the commune of Charenton-le-Pont lost about a third of its territory when the City of Paris annexed the Bois de Vincennes, a small part of which belonged to Charenton-le-Pont.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] Charenton-le-Pont is served by two stations on Paris Métro Line 8: Liberté and Charenton — Écoles.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] There was also another station in the commune that existed from 1849 to 1942 and then was demolished.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] As of 2015 the commune has 14 public and private schools.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] Charenton shares the association football club CA Paris-Charenton with the nearby town Maisons-Alfort.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] They are a merger between CA Paris (founded in 1892)—who won the 1920 Coupe de France, were second place in the 1928 Coupe de France, played in the first two seasons of Ligue 1, and then played in Ligue 2 until 1963—and SO Charentonnais (founded in 1904).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charenton-le-pont] They mainly play at the Stade Henri Guérin in Charenton, but also play many matches at the Stade Charentonneau in Maisons-Alfort.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby was born in Cowes on the Isle of Wight to Aaron and Juliana Manby, née Fewster.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Aaron Manby was a successful engineer building bridges, ships and engines.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] As a child Charles attended a Roman Catholic seminary; in 1814 he attended well disciplined Saint-Servan College near Rennes, but returned to England in 1815 having turned down the opportunity of joining the military under a commission organised by his uncle.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby's father was the founder, and from 1812, the managing partner of the Horseley Ironworks at Tipton, Staffordshire.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] In 1817, Charles began training as an engineer at the Ironworks working for such notable engineers as John Rennie and Thomas Telford.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] During his training he helped with projects at West India Docks and the iron paddleship which was named *Aaron Manby*.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] This was made in parts at the Ironworks and then transported to the Surrey Canal Dock on the River Thames in London.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] The ship was then reassembled with Charles Manby supervising the installation of the vessel's steam engine.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Despite being only 18 years old, Manby was designated as the chief engineer during its maiden voyage on 10 June 1822 with Sir Charles Napier as captain.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] During this voyage across the English Channel, the vessel became the first iron ship to carry cargo from London to Paris.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] In 1823 Manby started work installing hydrogen gas pipes in Paris, employed by the French company *Compagnie d'Carriage par de gaz Hydrogen*; The company had been founded by Daniel Wilson and Manby's father the year before.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Still employed in France by his father, Manby worked at a gas works at Ternes, then later reorganised the ironworks at Le Creusot.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby's fluency in the French language was an asset throughout his life.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby was then employed by the French government creating France's state-owned tobacco factories.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Charles then returned to the UK and took over the management of the Beaufort Iron Works in Beaufort, Blaenau Gwent where he married Ellen Jones in 1830.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] He briefly managed the Bristol Iron Works, but in 1834 he moved to London and began practising there as a civil engineer.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] He and Henry Cruger Price marketed the 'Price and Manby System' a new type of ventilation system for whole buildings.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] The business lasted until 1843 when their offices in Bristol and London closed.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby had become involved with the Arctic explorer Sir John Ross's India Steamship Company which he joined in 1838.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] The company's objective was to establish a steamship service to India, but it was quickly taken over by the Peninsular and Oriental Steam Navigation Company.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Charles Manby then became Secretary of the Institution of Civil Engineers (ICE) in November 1839, succeeding Thomas Webster.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] He nominally retired from this role in 1856 and was awarded a testimonial, a prize and a purse of 2,000 pounds from the chairman Robert Stephenson.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] The next secretary was Manby's former assistant James Forrest.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby remained involved in the organisation and participated in its activities as Honorary Secretary until his death.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby helped Samuel Colt's company to create a factory in Pimlico to manufacture firearms.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Colt had received a lot of interest in his revolvers at the Great Exhibition in 1851 and Manby had been involved in the organisation of the exhibition arranging financial underwriting for Sir Robert Peel.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby negotiated a lease with the British Government which enabled Colt to go into full production three years later.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Colt was able to make a profit during the Crimean War, but the factory closed in 1856 shortly after the end of the war.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] In 1853 Manby became a Fellow of the Royal Society and in 1856 he became the London representative of locomotive manufacturer Robert Stephenson and Company.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby moved next door to Stephenson and travelled across Europe to represent the locomotive company using the contacts which he had created during his 17 years as secretary of the ICE.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Charles Manby was chosen with James Rendel and John Robinson McClean to join the International Scientific Commission on the Suez Canal.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] This was based in Paris where his French language was again useful.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] His knowledge of engineering and his linguistic skills helped him serve as one of the secretaries to the International Commission for the piercing of the isthmus of Suez, with Jules Barthélemy-Saint-Hilaire and Lieutenant Lieussou.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] In 1858, Manby, by now a childless widower, married Harriet Willard, the widow of publisher W.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] He died on 31 July 1884, at Ranelagh House, 10 Lower Grosvenor Place, London.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] In 1860, Manby helped create the Engineer & Railway Volunteer Staff Corps (today, the British Army Reserve's Engineer and Logistic Staff Corps.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] As a result, Manby became a lieutenant-colonel.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Manby left an estate of just under £250.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/charles-manby] Today his home at 60 Westbourne Terrace in London is identified by a blue plaque.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] A **civil engineer** is a person who practices civil engineering – the application of planning, designing, constructing, maintaining, and operating infrastructure while protecting the public and environmental health, as well as improving existing infrastructure that may have been neglected.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] The term "civil engineer" was established by John Smeaton in 1750 to contrast engineers working on civil projects with the military engineers, who worked on armaments and defenses.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Over time, various sub-disciplines of civil engineering have become recognized and much of military engineering has been absorbed by civil engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Other engineering practices became recognized as independent engineering disciplines, including chemical engineering, mechanical engineering, and electrical engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In some places, a civil engineer may perform land surveying; in others, surveying is limited to construction surveying, unless an additional qualification is obtained.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Civil engineers usually practice in a particular specialty, such as construction engineering, geotechnical engineering, structural engineering, land development, transportation engineering, hydraulic engineering, sanitary engineering, and environmental engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] A civil engineer is concerned with determining the right design for these structures and looking after the construction process so that the longevity of these structures is guaranteed after completion.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] These structures should also be satisfactory for the public in terms of comfort.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Some civil engineers, particularly those working for government agencies, may practice across multiple specializations, particularly when involved in critical infrastructure development or maintenance.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Civil engineers generally work in a variety of locations and conditions.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Much of a civil engineer's work is dealing with non-engineers or others from different technical disciplines, so training should give skills preparing future civil engineers in organizational relationships between parties to projects, cost and time.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Many spend time outdoors at construction sites so that they can monitor operations or solve problems onsite.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] The job is typically a blend of in-office and on-location work depending on the focus of each engineer.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Work environment can vary significantly depending on specialization, such as structural, transportation, or geotechnical engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In many countries, civil engineers are subject to licensure.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In some jurisdictions with mandatory licensing, people who do not obtain a license may not call themselves "civil engineers".
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In Belgium, *Civil Engineer* (abbreviated **Ir.**) (French: *Ingénieur Civil*, Dutch: *Burgerlijk Ingenieur*) is a legally protected title applicable to graduates of the five-year engineering course of one of the six universities and the Royal Military Academy.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Their speciality can be all fields of engineering: civil, structural, electrical, mechanical, chemical, physics and even computer science.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] This use of the title may cause confusion to the English speaker as the Belgian "civil" engineer can have a speciality other than civil engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In fact, Belgians use the adjective "civil" in the sense of "civilian", as opposed to military engineers.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] The formation of the civil engineer has a strong mathematical and scientific base and is more theoretical in approach than the practical oriented industrial engineer (**Ing.**) educated in a five-year program at a polytechnic.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Traditionally, students were required to pass an entrance exam on mathematics to start civil engineering studies.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] This exam was abolished in 2004 for the Flemish Community, but is still organised in the French Community.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Today the degree spans over all fields within engineering, including civil engineering, mechanical engineering, computer science, and electronics engineering, among others.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] There is generally a slight difference between a Master of Science in Engineering degree and the Scandinavian civil engineer degree, the latter's programme having closer ties with the industry's demands.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] A civil engineer is the better-known of the two; still, the area of expertise remains obfuscated for most of the public.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] A noteworthy difference is the mandatory courses in mathematics and physics, regardless of the equivalent master's degree, e.g. computer science.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] This is because the higher educational system is not fully adapted to the international standard graduation system, since it is treated as a professional degree.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Today (2009) this is starting to change due to the Bologna process.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] A Scandinavian *civilingenjör* will in international contexts commonly use the title of "Master of Science in Engineering" and will occasionally wear an engineering class ring.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] At the Norwegian Institute of Technology (now the Norwegian University of Science and Technology), the tradition with an NTH Ring goes back to 1914, before the Canadian iron ring.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In Spain, a civil engineering degree can be obtained after four years of study in the various branches of mathematics, physics, mechanics, etc.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] The earned degree is called *Grado en Ingeniería Civil*.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Further studies at a graduate school include master's and doctoral degrees.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Before the current situation, that is, before the implementation of Bologna Process in 2010, a degree in civil engineering in Spain could be obtained after three to six years of study and was divided into two main degrees.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In the first case, the earned degree was called *Ingeniero Técnico de Obras Públicas* (*ITOP*), literally translated as "Public Works Engineer" obtained after three years of study and equivalent to a Bachelor of Civil Engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] This degree is equivalent to a Master of Civil Engineering and is obtained after five or six years of study depending on the school granting the title.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Both schools now belong to the Technical University of Madrid.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Mechanical and Electrical engineering tasks are included under the Industrial engineering degree.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] A chartered civil engineer (known as certified or professional engineer in other countries) is a member of the Institution of Civil Engineers, and has also passed membership exams.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] However, a non-chartered civil engineer may be a member of the Institution of Civil Engineers or the Institution of Civil Engineering Surveyors.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] The description "civil engineer" is not restricted to members of any particular professional organisation although "chartered civil engineer" is.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Even many polytechnic tertiary schools give out separate degrees for each field of study.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Typically study in geology, geodesy, structural engineering and urban engineering allows a person to obtain a degree in construction engineering.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Mechanical engineering, automotive engineering, hydraulics and even sometimes metallurgy are fields in a degree in "Machinery Engineering".
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] In the United States, civil engineers are typically employed by municipalities, construction firms, consulting engineering firms, architect/engineer firms, the military, state governments, and the federal government.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Each state requires engineers who offer their services to the public to be licensed by the state.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Licensure is obtained by meeting specified education, examination, and work experience requirements.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] After completing these steps and the granting of licensure by a state board, engineers may use the title "Professional Engineer" or PE in advertising and documents.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Most states have implemented mandatory continuing education requirements to maintain a license.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] The ASCE (American Society of Civil Engineers) represents more than 150,000 members of the civil engineering profession worldwide.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Official members of the ASCE must hold a bachelor's degree from an accredited civil engineering program and be a licensed professional engineer or have five years responsible charge of engineering experience.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Most civil engineers join this organization to be updated of current news, projects, and methods (such as sustainability) related to civil engineering as well as contribute their expertise and knowledge to other civil engineers and students obtaining their civil engineering degree.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] The ICE (Institution of Civil Engineers) founded in 1818, represents, as of 2008, more than 80,000 members of the civil engineering profession worldwide.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Its commercial arm, Thomas Telford Ltd, provides training, recruitment, publishing and contract services.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Founded in 1887, the CSCE (Canadian Society for Civil Engineering) represents members of the Canadian civil engineering profession.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Official members of the CSCE must hold a bachelor's degree from an accredited civil engineering program.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Most civil engineers join this organization to be updated of current news, projects, and methods (such as sustainability) related to civil engineering; as well as contribute their expertise and knowledge to other civil engineers and students obtaining their civil engineering degree.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/civil-engineer] Local sections frequently host events such as seminars, tours, and courses.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] Born in Glasgow in 1970, he left Scotland after his chemistry studies for Dublin, but then went to London in 1817 to the home of Aaron Manby (1776–1850), also an engineer, who headed the Horseley steel factory.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] Manby supplied the Gas Light and Coke Company, and Wilson acted as his agent.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] In 1819, Wilson and Manby moved their attention to France under the restored Bourbon monarchy to supply the emerging new French gas industry.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] The two men became business associates and in 1822 they set up the "Forges de Charenton" (the Charenton Iornworks), and in 1826 bought the "Forges du Creusot" (the Creusot Iornworks).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] Both companies would become bankrupt in 1833 after the chaos of the 1830 July Revolution.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] They developed patents for the use of gas in lighting.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] By 1825, the company had built a gasworks in the Ternes district in Paris, and in 1829 the company provided the gas to illuminate the Rue de la Paix.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] The venture would make Wilson very wealthy, and it survived as an independent operation until 1847 when all the Paris gas companies were merged into a single entity.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] On 25 June 1835 in Paris, Wilson married Antoinette Henriette Casenave, daughter of French politician, Antoine Casenave.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] Casenave was from a family of magistrates and parliamentarians.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] The couple lived in the old 2nd arrondissement of Paris and had three children, Marguerite (born on 24 May 1836), Marie-Anne Berthe (born on 23 July 1838), and Daniel junior (born on 6 March 1840).
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] Casenave died in Paris on 5 August 1843, followed by her second child Marie-Anne on 21 February 1845 in Paris.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] Daniel died in his Château d'Écoublay in Fontenay-Trésigny on 2 September 1849.
[src:aaron-manby-ironmaster/daniel-wilson-chemist] — Minutes of the Proceedings of the Institution of Civil Engineers, Volume 9, London 1850.
